SIMPLE: consociate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Consociate
<hw>Con*so"ci*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>consociatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>consociare</ets> to associate,
unite; <ets>con-</ets> + <ets>sociare</ets> to join, unite. See
<er>Social</er>.]</ety> <def>An associate; an accomplice.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Wicked <xex>consociates</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Consociate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Consociate
<hw>Con*so"ci*ate</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Consociated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Consociating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
bring into alliance, confederacy, or relationship; to bring together; to
join; to unite.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Join pole to pole, <qex>consociate</qex> severed worlds.</q>
<rj><qau>Mallet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite in an ecclesiastical consociation.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Consociate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Consociate
<hw>Con*so"ci*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be allied,
confederated, or associated; to coalescence.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bentley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form an ecclesiastical consociation.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Consociation</ent>⟦br⟧
